[normal]Written evidence submitted by the [bold]England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) [bold][WAS0034][bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Contents[bold]&#xa0;[bold]1.[bold]              [bold]Introduction[bold]&#xa0;[bold]2.[bold]              [bold]Grassroots Development and Facilities – Building Solid Foundations in School[bold]2.1[bold]              [bold]Asda Kwik [bold]Cricket[bold]2.2[bold]              [bold]Chance to Shin[bold]e[bold]2.3[bold]              [bold]Lady Taverners[bold]2.4[bold]              [bold]Future School Sport Funding[bold]3.[bold]              [bold]Grassroots development and facilities – Club Cricket and community programmes[bold]3.1[bold]              [bold]Coaches[bold]3.2[bold]              [bold]Officials[bold]3.3[bold]              [bold]Capital Investment into Facilities[bold]3.4[bold]              [bold]Protection of Local [bold]Authority and School pitches[bold]4.[bold]              [bold]International and Elite programme development and facilities  [bold]4.1[bold]              [bold]S[bold]ustained success on the International Stage[bold]4.2[bold]              [bold]ICC framework for promoting Women’s Cricket[bold]&#xa0;[bold]4.3[bold]              [bold]Targeting Sustained Success [bold]&#xa0;[bold]5.1[bold]              [bold]Media Partnerships[bold]6.[bold]              [bold]Growing Participation in Cricket[bold]7.[bold]              [bold]Conclusion[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) is the national governing body for cricket in England and Wales. 
[normal]Our vision is to inspire the nation to choose cricket. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Our responsibility is to promote and develop the game at all levels and in recent years we h
[normal]ave invested a great deal of expertise and resource into modernising our structures to ensure that we can effectively support and develop cricket at all levels of the game, including women’s and girls’ cricket.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Sixteen years ago the ECB took over responsi
[normal]bility from the Women’s Cricket Association as the National Governing Body for women and girls cricket 
[normal]In this time we have made tremendous progress in growing and promoting the women’s and girls’ game at all levels. 
[normal] 
[normal]Women’s and girls’ cricket is more or
[normal]ganised, better funded and has wider exposure than ever before with more people participating not only as players but in many different roles – including coaching, umpiring and volunteering.
[normal]One of the most significant achievements is that women’s cricket 
[normal]is now fully integrated within the ECB, from international level to development programmes
[normal].  T
[normal]he women’s game sits inside the same structures with the same reporting lines.  It is completely embedded in the or
[normal]ganisational
[normal] structure and has become an integr
[normal]al part of the cricket family within the ECB’s Cricket Partnerships and 
[normal]England Cricket Departments
[normal]. 
[normal]At present there are two women on ECB’s main Board
[normal]: 
[normal]former Chief Constable Jane Stichbury who is an Independent Director providing strategic support to ou
[normal]r anti-corruption unit and Baroness Rachel Heyhoe-Flint
[normal] OBE DL
[normal], a former high profile England International and Women’s Cricket representative who has championed the women’s game for many years.
[normal]As with the 
[normal]men’s 
[normal]game, the vast majority of our investment i
[normal]s focused into developing grassroots opportunities, developing player pathways and top-class support structures for elite players. 
[normal] 
[normal]This approach ensures we have a “product” from the elite end to the very grassroots which is compelling, competitive and sus
[normal]tainable.
[normal]On the international stage, ECB investment and on-going commitment has seen the England Women’s team secure continued success including lifting the ICC World Cup in Sydney in 2009, retaining their number 
[normal]one
[normal] 
[normal]world ranking from 2009 to 2013 and this summer beating Australia to regain the Ashes – and win the inaugural multi-format Women’s Ashes Series (which comprised one Test match, 
[normal]three
[normal] 
[normal]NatWest 
[normal]ODIs and 
[normal]three
[normal] 
[normal]NatWest 
[normal]T20s). 
[normal]At the grassroots level
[normal], 
[normal]the last 
[normal]ten years has seen a 507% increase in the number of cricket clubs with a Women’s and/or a 
[normal]g
[normal]irl’s section (from 93 to 565). 
[normal] 
[normal]We have had huge success in attracting young girls to the sport and we have exciting plans to retain a greater percentage of them th
[normal]rough their teenage years and into adulthood and ultimately, for those with the ability, into a clearly defined and maturing talent pathway.
[normal]Not only has ECB made women’s cricket part of its core business so too have the 39 County Cricket Boards (CCBs). 
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]he CCBs are the game’s local delivery network and with support and investment from both ECB and Sport England in recent years the women’s game is now central to their strategic plans
[normal]There remains a significant challenge to secure wider media coverage and commercial value for 
[normal]w
[normal]omen’s 
[normal]c
[normal]ricket. 
[normal] 
[normal]The ECB will continue to pioneer new formats and invest directly to achieve these aims, building on the success we have had already in promotion
[normal]al activity including “double headers” where 
[normal]international w
[normal]omen’s Twenty20 fixtures are played immediately before the men’s match, 
[normal]investing 
[normal]in broadcasts of non-televised matches on YouTube and creating a new 
[normal]points based multi-
[normal]format 
[normal]s
[normal]eries 
[normal]to widen and
[normal] sustain interest 
[normal]throughout the summer
[normal].
[normal]In this submission we highlight some of the successes to date, some of the challenges we face and set out how we are committed to ensuring that women’s cricket continues to thrive and provide women and girls with 
[normal]outstanding opportunities.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Children should be introduced to physical activity opportunities (physical literacy) at an early age as part of their personal and emotional developme
[normal]nt and then in time to competitive sport. It is vital that this development process is driven within the school system. 
[normal] 
[normal]We believe that young girls should be given the same opportunities to play and try sport without any stigma that the sport is only ‘for
[normal] boys’.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Our priority is to ensure delivery of as many opportunities as possible for girls to develop a lasting interest in cricket and continue to play the sport for years to come.  
[normal]To deliver this the ECB has invested millions of pounds over the last fe
[normal]w years into partnerships with other cricket bodies and the private sector to build programmes that help 
[normal]grow 
[normal]cricket in schools, especially state schools
[normal],
[normal] and make full use of the facilities they offer. 
[normal]Each partnership programme offers a fantastic oppor
[normal]tunity for girls to participate in cricket from a young age either through offering
[normal] both mixed sessions and/or specific courses for girls. 
[normal]2.1
[normal]              
[normal]Asda Kwik Cricket
[normal]The ECB’s flagship grassroots schools initiative is Kwik 
[normal]Cricket
[normal],
[normal] in its 8
[normal]th
[normal] year of sponsorship
[normal] with Asda
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] It provides children at primary school a fun, inclusive, fast-paced introduction to the game of cricket
[normal] 
[normal]and offers both mixed sessions along with a programme designed specifically for girls
[normal]. 
[normal]The current competition boasts 
[normal]participation figures of 140,000 with over 50% of all primary schools entering the competition.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]The girls
[normal]’
[normal] only programme had over 30,000 girls 
[normal]play 
[normal]in 2013, a 38% increase from 2012.
[normal]The main aim of the competition is to inspire children to play cricket 
[normal]through the means of a national competition framework delivered by our 39
[normal] CCBs
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]The 
[normal]programme provides
[normal] teachers 
[normal]with a range of resources
[normal] 
[normal]including skills 
[normal]demonstrations, 
[normal]ideas to play the game, an interactive web site, equipment and resources
[normal] 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]certificates and badges.
[normal]2.2
[normal]              
[normal]Chance to Shine
[normal]The Chance to 
[normal]Shine
[normal] programme is run by the Cricket Foundation 
[normal]charity and is currently in its 8
[normal]th
[normal] year of delivery and is part funded by the ECB.
[normal] 
[normal] It has delivered cricket lessons to over 
[normal]two
[normal] 
[normal]million children in 
[normal]7,000
[normal] schools across the UK.
[normal] 
[normal] The aim of the programme is to reintroduce cricket into state schools and use cricket as a tool for the wider developmental issues like behaviour, attainment, team work and life skills 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]values.
[normal]Chance to
[normal] Shine supports the wider development of girls and cricket by working in partnership with the ECB to place girl’s cricket development at the forefront of every project. 
[normal] 
[normal]There are approximately 160,000 girls playing cricket in school annually through the C
[normal]hance to 
[normal]Shine
[normal] programme
[normal] 
[normal]and it will reach the one millionth girl to have gone through the programme during this school term
[normal]. The programme will continue to expand its reach into both Primary and Secondary Schools (with a new focus on 14-16 year olds based
[normal] on Sport England funding) offering more girls the chance to receive high quality coaching and the ECB will be looking to increase the numbers entering the club network on the back of this. 
[normal]The project has partnerships with 1,004 local cricket clubs, and 
[normal]qualified cricket coaches provide coaching and competition to local primary and secondary schools.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]Of those children going on to join a local club, 31% of these were girls. 
[normal]Seven members of the current England’s Women Cricket Team, including the captain 
[normal]Charlotte Edwards
[normal] MBE
[normal], are employed by the Cricket Foundation as Chance to Shine Coaching Ambassadors and have made an enormous impact as positive role models in schools and clubs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The Ambassador programme has been running since 2008 and so far 11 England
[normal] Women have worked inside both schools and community programmes. 15,000 school girls were coached by the seven England Women ambassadors last year.
