[normal]Coaches
[normal] 
[normal]The number of female coaches has grown from 556 in 2003 to 2,756 in 2013.
[normal]Eight CCBs are involved in project 500,
[normal] a County Sport Partnership / UK Sport project which is working with 5 NGB’s to develop programmes and opportunities for female coaches in their sports. The ECB will develop this programme nationally and roll it across our CCB network.
[normal]ECB are in the proce
[normal]ss of developing new courses
[normal] and resources
[normal] to 
[normal]further 
[normal]improve 
[normal]coaches’ 
[normal]soft skills to 
[normal]help them 
[normal]engage 
[normal]more 
[normal]effectively with women and girls.
[normal]3.2
[normal]              
[normal]Officials
[normal] 
[normal]As part of our integrated approach the ECB is committed to offering opportunities
[normal] to women
[normal] across a
[normal]ll sections of the game including offering and providing training to 
[normal]those 
[normal]who want to become umpires and scorers
[normal] within a membership arm called the ECB ACO (Association of Cricket Officials). 
[normal]Several counties have begun to provide female only courses in support of the growth of female umpires. 
[normal] 
[normal]Further steps have been taken to source female official role models from the success of the England Women’s teams. 
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Active promotion of female official
[normal]s is one of the main priorities for the ECB ACO and recent work has been undertaken to identify and remove the key barriers to females following the officials’ pathway through to all levels of the game. 
[normal]Female umpires are becoming more prominent
[normal] – within 
[normal]the last few years female umpires have been appointed to umpire both Minor Counties and County Second Eleven cricket and further examples exist in Premier 
[normal]Leagues
[normal]. 
[normal]Late in 2012 ECB ACO launched a national initiative to develop and engage more females in u
[normal]mpiring.  Having established a robust pathway for all umpires to follow, it is now open to all umpires of the appropriate ability, irrespective of gender and race, to attain appointments at all levels of the game. 
[normal] 
[normal]This includes developing Umpires at the v
[normal]ery highest level of the game and ECB is about to launch an inclusive scheme to provide top level female umpires with opportunities to demonstrate their umpiring ability and to progress towards involvement in the professional game.
[normal]There are currently fema
[normal]le scorers involved at all levels of the game (including international level)
[normal], and the intention is to mirror this in the umpiring arena
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Case Study – [bold]female umpires in the [bold]Northumberland Cricket League [bold]In 2011 
[normal]Officials Gillian Woodley and Sarah Lee have
[normal] become the first two women to take charge of a match in one of the North’s top leagues
[normal].
[normal] Gillian is a fully qualified umpire having attained her Level Two 
[normal]qualification 
[normal]last year. Sarah previously scored for Blyth Second XI and this is her second season um
[normal]piring, after passing her Level One from the English Cricket Board’s Association of Cricket Officials.
[normal]Gillian, from Gosforth, Newcastle, said: “I admit I once hated the sport but I was becoming a cricket widow because my husband loves it. I had to grow to
[normal] like it just to see him at weekends. 
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]I started as a scorer and got hooked so I decided to get my qualifications at the same time as Peter. It’s a fascinating sport and I love it now. I think I’ve gained respect from the men players.
[normal] 
[normal] It was difficult at first when I did my first matches four years ago because I think some men found it hard to accept decisions from a woman. 
[normal] 
[normal]But I think now I’ve shown I can do it and it’s something I very much enjoy.
[normal] 
[normal] It would be lovely to see more wom
[normal]en doing it. There’s a great team spirit among the umpires, but it’s always nice to see a few women walking out there.”
[normal]Sarah, from Blyth, Northumberland, is studying A-levels at Newcastle College but spends her weekends 
[normal]at cricket matches
[normal] across the county.
[normal]  
[normal]She first attended a cricket match aged just three months with her dad, a keen player.
[normal](Case study used from the local paper – the Chronicle live) 
[normal]3.3
[normal]              
[normal]Capital Investment into Facilities
[normal]Through the last Sport England funding period the ECB have targeted women’s and girls’ participation through capital investment – identifying where access to facilities are barriers and require investment to increase participation. Over the 4 year period t
[normal]he ECB invested £5.4m to specifically support women and girls cricket. This totalled 57 awards across approximately 26 projects with the majority of these going to our recreational clubs. Supporting this capital investment, first class counties and clubs e
[normal]nsured revenue funding was aligned to support growth in women’s cricket. 
[normal]Initial statistics have seen increases in participation across the awards with a 72% increase amongst 5 – 15 year olds and 40% increase in participation of 16 – 24 year olds. 
[normal]In add
[normal]ition to this targeted funding, other revenue and capital investment is made available to support club programmes and the wider network to support women and girls cricket and clubs within England and Wales.
[normal]3.4
[normal]              
[normal]Protection of Local Authority and School pitc
[normal]hes
[normal]In order for Women and Girls’ participation to continue to grow they must have access to decent local facilities and pitches. 
[normal] 
[normal]Over 40% of cricket is played on local authority pitches and Central Government must make sure that local leisure provision i
[normal]s a key 
[normal]criterion 
[normal]by which local authorities are held to account for their spending by the Department for Communities and Local Government. 
[normal] 
[normal]As sport is not a statutory service it too often a soft option for cuts. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]ECB welcomed the enhanced protections ou
[normal]tlined in the Government’s National Planning Policy framework but remains very concerned at the on-going threat to the infrastructure of pitches and facilities available to sports within the local authority framework which is under extreme budgetary pressu
[normal]res. 
[normal] 
[normal]Playing fields are also under threat from developers on certain sites such as Civil Service grounds.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Greater effort needs to go into provision of pitches and facilities. 
[normal] 
[normal]Whether these are maintained by local authorities, volunteer groups or cricket
[normal] clubs on-going support needs to be given to addressing the poor state of pitches and increasing quality standards.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Recently all of the major pitch sports have jointly with Sport England, revised the planning model for local authority playing pitch strate
[normal]gies.
[normal] 
[normal] Through this model all pitch sports have committed to collaborating and working with Local Authorities on the strategic provision of sport. 
[normal] 
[normal]Supply, demand, disposal and quality are all measured through this process.
[normal]4.[bold]              [bold]International and Elite programme development and facilities  [bold]For many years there were envious glances from all UK NGBs to the facilities and research centres and programmes in other countries. Cricket was no
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]different. 
[normal] 
[normal]Cricket Australia's centre of exc
[normal]ellence was always seen as the benchmark in this regard. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However, in 2003 the National Cricket Performance
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Centre at
[normal] 
[normal]Loughborough
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]University was
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]opened
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]by Her Majesty 
[normal]The
[normal] Queen,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]and has
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]now established itself as the leading cricket centre in the world. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The centre employs
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]25 full time staff
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]and delivers world class programmes in terms of cricket and areas such as science and medicine and provides the game in England and Wales with leading edge research.
[normal] 
[normal] The coaching courses created and the science and m
[normal]edicine innovations
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]permeate throughout the game and the centre itself is used by a wide range of teams from grassroots school levels to the England elite squads.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Indeed the Elite Coach development Programme is recognised as the foremost cricket coach ed
[normal]ucation programme in the world.  It has also provided an elite coaching benchmark which other UK sports have sought to follow by seeking advice directly from the ECB.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]All England Women’s Cricket Pathway programmes (players and staff) benefit from this wor
[normal]ld-leading resource: from the England Women’s Development Programme U15 through to the full England Women’s Programme.  All winter training camps ate staged at the National Cricket Performance Centre with matches also staged at Loughborough during the seas
[normal]on.
