[normal]4.1
[normal]              
[normal]S
[normal]ustained success on the International Stage
[normal]The England Women
[normal] Squad
[normal] has secured unprecedented success on the international stage in recent years culminating in being ranked the world number one 
[normal]ODI 
[normal]team from 2009 to 2013 and regaining the Ashes 
[normal]with a resounding victory against Australia, the new world champions, in August 2013.
[normal]This success comes as a result of the full integration of elite women’s cricket into the England Cricket Department at ECB. This integration has yielded more of the suppo
[normal]rt services needed to 
[normal]perform at a world class level – specialist coaching, medical screening, bespoke strength and conditioning programmes and access to the very best facilities.
[normal]The England 
[normal]Women’s 
[normal]squad players are now semi-professional and benefit from
[normal] membership of the PCA – the Professional Cricketers’ Association. 
[normal]The England Women’s team play their internationals at some of the finest grounds in the country.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The 2013 Ashes matches were played in all corners of the country including Lord’s Cricket 
[normal]Ground, Ageas Bowl (Southampton), ICG Emirates Durham, Chelmsford, and Hove.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Whilst the majority of women’s internationals are staged at First Class County grounds, ECB also takes international women’s cricket to out-grounds and to festivals such as Tru
[normal]ro CC (Cornish Festival of Cricket 2012) and Louth CC, Lincolnshire (SO Festival 2013).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The vision here is that international women’s cricket can have a huge impact in the more remote parts of the country and in acting as a catalyst for growth in the fema
[normal]le game.
