[normal]              
[normal]ICC framework for promoting Women’s Cricket
[normal]              
[normal]The ICC 
[normal]Females in Cricket Strategy (which sits within ICC’s Strategic Plan) has set a target of a minimum of 1 million women participants across the world by the end of 2015.  The current estimate suggests there are some 650,000 players around the world.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The ECB were lead proponents of the decision taken by the ICC that the World Twenty20 tournaments in 2009, 2010 &amp; 2012 were to be joint men’s and women’s events - generating increased profile and exposure for the women’s game around the world. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4.
[normal]3
[normal]              
[normal]Targe
[normal]ting
[normal] Sustained
[normal] 
[normal]S
[normal]uccess
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]ECB has set itself the target of developing the world’s best players to win the ICC World Twenty20 in 2014, 2016 and 2018 and the ICC Women’s World Cup in England in 2017.  One of our key ambitions is to for the England Women’s 
[normal]Academy to develop an effective supply of players capable of performing for England from 2014 and at world’s best level from 2018.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The England Women’s Development Programme U19 is designed to develop an effective supply of players to the England Women’s 
[normal]Academy from 2014 capable of performing for England from 2017 and at world’s best level from 2021. Both the England Women’s Development Programmes at U19 and U15 level and the inaugural England Women’s U19 overseas tour (South Africa) is to become an annua
[normal]l event.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Underpinning this development the ECB in partnership with Sport England invest into the further development of a robust Talent ID system to detect the country’s highest potential players from within Counties.  There is a mentoring Programme imple
[normal]mented for England Women’s Academy to be rolled out with all England Women’s Development Programme U19 players from 2014 alongside the implementation of regional skills based coaching sessions delivered by Lead Specialist Coaches for all England Women’s Cr
[normal]icket Pathway 
[normal]fast bowlers, spin bowlers, wicket-keepers and batters
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]One of the most challenging areas in trying to develop and grow wo
[normal]men’s cricket is securing an increased media profile to help drive 
[normal]public interest and 
[normal]commercial success.
[normal]There is still a long way to go and the reality is that women’s cricket is still subsidised from revenues generated by the men’s international game a
[normal]nd requires cross promotional support and subsidy in the commercial field and targeted public sector investment. ECB’s commercial strategy is to centralise all England team sponsorships – meaning all England teams (Men, Women, Lions, development sides, 
[normal]D
[normal]is
[normal]abilit
[normal]ies
[normal]) share the same Team Sponsor. 
[normal] 
[normal]From 2014
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]Waitrose 
[normal]will be the 
[normal]main 
[normal]Team Sponsor 
[normal]with kit provided by adidas.  From a perception point of view it is important for the women’s team to have an association with 
[normal]these
[normal] 
[normal]premium
[normal], well-known brands as it
[normal] helps reiterate and promote the professionalism of the game.
[normal]However, whilst our current view is that the teams should share the Team Sponsor, the ECB will longer-term continue to explore additional standalone commercial deals for the women’s team – and h
[normal]as employed a new business manager devoted specifically to targeting these opportunities. 
[normal]This summer, the ECB secured its first “stand
[normal]-
[normal]alone” sponsorship for the Women’s team - Kia Motors came on board for the Women’s Ashes Series providing the team with
[normal] cars for the duration of the Series.
[normal] 
[normal] Whilst the deal did not have any significant financial benefit for the team nor organisation, it shows that there is an appetite from brands to be associated with successful women’s sports teams –albeit on a much smal
[normal]ler scale.
[normal] 
[normal] For comparison, Jaguar – the men’s team car supplier – provides cars in addition to £300k in sponsorship monies.
[normal]England Women tend to play a mixture of One Day Internationals (ODIs; 50 overs) and Twenty20 matches (it is only in the Women’s Ash
[normal]es Series where they 
[normal]also 
[normal]compete in one four-day Test match). In previous years, these formats have been sponsored by NatWest – as they also sponsored the men’s ODIs and T20s. 
[normal] 
[normal]From 2014, NatWest will become the title sponsor of all T20 cricket (men’s, wo
[normal]men’s and grassroots). The ECB is currently sourcing a new sponsor for the ODI format, who we envisage will become the game-wide sponsor of the one-day format, including Women’s ODIs.
[normal]We are also optimistic that the ICC Women’s Committee will create a bi-l
[normal]ateral programme amongst the top 8 teams over the next 3 years to 
[normal]enable us to market international women's cricket with a longer lead time and therefore give the ECB Commercial team more to work with and much stronger assets to sell. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]For comparison in 
[normal]the cricket world, Cricket Australia 
[normal]adopt
[normal] a similar strategy by ‘bolting-on’ women’s sponsorships onto the men’s team packages. CA 
[normal]have
[normal] not been able to secure any stand-alone sponsorships for the women’s team. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The one major difference between ECB and C
[normal]A is their choice of branding and communications strategy for the Women’s team - the Australia Women’s team is branded as the ‘Southern Stars’ and have their own social media channels. 
[normal] 
[normal]For reference, Southern Stars twitter feed has 8,700 followers compare
[normal]d to the CA’s overall following of 223,200. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]Whilst the ECB is exploring separating its digital media channels for each team or competition, our current view is that sending women’s messages to our entire database (circa 1.5m across all channels) does mor
[normal]e to boost the profile of women’s cricket/ the England team, than sending to a smaller, targeted audience as CA choose to do.  Both approaches have their merits and we keep this area under close review in order maximise our reach.
[normal]The profile of women’s cr
[normal]icket will only grow through sustained, mass media interest leading to increased spectator following and commercial income.
[normal] 
[normal]Securing mass
[normal] media coverage 
[normal]remains a challenge
[normal], but t
[normal]he ECB notes and welcome
[normal]s
[normal] the further progress made by broadcasters and the media since the London Olympics. Sky’s viewing figures of the recent Women’s Ashes were the 
[normal]best ever for international women’s cricket in this country and Sky described 2013 as “a breakthrough summer for 
[normal]women’s cricket”.
[normal]The ECB itself 
[normal]continues to heavily invest in marketing activity to help profile the Women’s team and fixtures
[normal] as highlighted in case study 5.
[normal]The ECB provides rights-free imagery to media for every match (through Getty), and after every 
[normal]day’s play and training session - a player is put up for media interviews. If media cannot attend these sessions, ECB records interviews and sends to them via our Audioboo site.
[normal] 
[normal] In addition, video highlights of every women’s international – regardless of 
[normal]whether it’s televised or not – are posted on the ECB’s digital platforms.
[normal]In addition to this ‘business as usual’ activity, ECB arranged 4 ‘life-style’ photo-shoots to present the team in a different light – one as part of a promotional shoot for suit mak
[normal]er TM Lewin, one taken at Wormsley Cricket Ground (before the Women’s Ashes Test), one at Brighton sea-front (before the NatWest ODI at Hove), and another beneath the Angel of the North – with the Women’s Ashes Series trophy in shot.
[normal]During ECB promotional
[normal] activity for the grassroots game – a women’s player is always offered up to media alongside a men’s player. For example, in April 2013 Charlotte Edwards joined Alastair Cook at Harrow Town CC to promote NatWest CricketForce – a nationwide initiative where
[normal] 2,000 clubs hold an event to prepare their ground for the season ahead.
