[normal]Media partnerships
[normal]The ECB’s two major broadcast partners – Sky Sports and BBC Radio – are committed supporters of the women’s game, and their increased coverage reflects the increasing interest in women’s cricket. 
[normal]Sky Sports began broadcasting women’s cricket seventeen yea
[normal]rs ago (June 1996 v New Zealand), and aired 
[normal]four
[normal] of the 
[normal]seven
[normal] Women’s Ashes Series matches live this summer.  Sky have aired
[normal] the majority
[normal] 
[normal]of England women’s home T20 matches live during the past 5 years, including the team winning the ICC Women’s World Cup
[normal] and World Twenty20 in 2009. Sky routinely undertake player interviews and broadcast promotional events on Sky Sports News and Cricket AM, as well as background pieces featuring key players during the intervals of men’s internationals. 
[normal]BBC Radio covered t
[normal]he first ever England Women’s T20 match at Hove in 2004, and have reported on every 
[normal]Women’s
[normal] World Cup.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Earlier this year, for the first time they broadcast all of England’s games in a World Cup – as well as sending a network TV crew and a reporter for BBC
[normal] 
[normal]Online
[normal] to India the 
[normal]host country
[normal].
[normal]  BBC Radio also covered the Women’s Ashes in 2005 and 2009, and this summer carried ball-by-ball commentary on all 
[normal]seven
[normal] Women’s Ashes Series matches.
[normal]On a smaller scale, The Times is the ECB’s Official Newspaper partner, and the ECB promoted the Women’s Ashes Series with a ticket promotion in-paper and online a few months prior to the matches – giving away 100 tickets for 
[normal]three
[normal] games, helping to raise a
[normal]wareness of the Ashes Series. 
[normal]National newspapers continue to support the women’s game, but like other sports no doubt share our frustration, space given is minimal. Coverage for Women’s cricket peaks during Ashes matches and World Cups. 
[normal]The Women’s Ashe
[normal]s Series format was announced on 13 May, and since then 11 matches have been played (
[normal]four
[normal] against 
[normal]Pakistan,
[normal] and 
[normal]seven
[normal] against Australia). These matches generated 86 items of national print coverage – reaching a total audience of 44.1 million.
[normal]The 
[normal]ECB looks
[normal] toward Government to place greater focus on public service broadcasters to cover women and girls sport within their schedules, including magazine and coaching programmes, as part of their broadcast licence arrangements
[normal]. Additional pressure on Sports Edito
[normal]rs would also be welcomed.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The ECB approach, as documented in 
[normal]this submission, is to create a fully accessible sport at every level of the game to ensure that we continue to grow the sport and make the right interventions to remove as many of the barriers to playing as possible.
[normal]There are many well documented reasons
[normal] for a drop out in sport - physical, environmental and social factors all can play their part to greater or lesser extent and the ECB is keen to understand 
[normal]more and to make sure our programmes adapt and meet the needs and requirements of those women and gi
[normal]rls wanting to participate in the sport. In reality it is the same barriers that prevent women playing as men. 
[normal]One of the key interventions a National Governing Body (NGB), such as the ECB, can make is to promote physical literacy at an early age, as part
[normal] of a young person’s personal and emotional development and then in time provide the right opportunities to play competitively. It can provide teachers with the necessary training and coaching support to help young people begin to develop a habit for life.
[normal] In our view it is vital that this development process is driven within the school system, to allow sports such as cricket to create a development journey from childhood to adulthood with different opportunities to play to meet the demand.
[normal]As outlined, the
[normal] ECB through its partnerships has well established programmes at primary school level such 
[normal]Asda 
[normal]Kwik Cricket which has a huge reach offering both mixed and programmes focused specifically on girls. 
[normal]Since receiving a major National Lottery investment from S
[normal]port England in April 2013
[normal], t
[normal]he Cricket Foundation is also embarking on a change in the way they work and a shift in priority to secondary schools.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Through Chance to 
[normal]Shine
[normal], they have 
[normal]begun creating strong links between community sports clubs and schools w
[normal]ith the help of County Cricket Board. Local cricket clubs are enabled to work closely with coaches, young people and teachers to set up a satellite cricket club on school sites; making it easier for young people to make the transition to clubs in the commu
[normal]nity. 
[normal]It
[normal] has already recently reached the milestone of its 500th school-based or ‘satellite’ cricket club.  
[normal]Pupils are at the heart of the decision-making and influence how their school club is run. 
[normal] 
[normal]Activity at the clubs range from extra-curricular coaching and forums to discussions on club activity, organising social events and ambassador visits.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]The aim of the scheme is two-fold: first, to help reduce the number of children leaving the game when th
[normal]ey move from primary to secondary school and, second, to contribute to a lower drop-off rate in sport among teenagers, especially in the 14 to 16 year age group. 
[normal] 
[normal]Over the next three years Chance to 
[normal]Shine
[normal] will look to work with 1250 secondary schools to es
[normal]tablish Satellite Clubs to improve the transition from school to community cricket.
[normal]To gain a greater understanding 
[normal]of participation 
[normal]across all ages, the ECB 
[normal]has recently commissioned a significant research project called Eureka! 
[normal]that
[normal] seeks to give specifi
[normal]c insight from current, lapsed and non-players. 
[normal] 
[normal]This will be used nationally and locally to better inform planning and programme design for women and girls. Early indications suggest that young people will continue to play more 
[normal]cricket 
[normal]with better signpos
[normal]ting of opportunities at local clubs and teams with proactive contact in schools to establish these links. 
[normal] 
[normal]This places more focus on expanding our school club links going forward.
[normal]There is significant potential to grow even further the game for women over
[normal] the age of 14 and will be looking to provide a different range of options based on this insight and in both cricket clubs and a range of different environments. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]ECB has also recently established a dedicated programme to work with further and higher educ
[normal]ation institutions to ensure that the drop off rate after leaving school is reduced and is working in partnership to deliver new programmes such as Last Man Stands.
